│ stop({"edit_points": [[238, 238, "llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/SCCP.cpp"]], "thoughts": "### │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe crash is an assertion failure, `pred_empty(DelBB)`,   │
│ within `DomTreeUpdater::validateDeleteBB`. This means that the `ipsccp` pass is         │
│ attempting to delete a `BasicBlock` that still has predecessors, which is an invalid    │
│ transformation. A block can only be safely deleted if it is unreachable, meaning it has │
│ no predecessors.\n\nThe backtrace points to `runIPSCCP` at `SCCP.cpp:251` as the        │
│ culprit calling for the deletion of this block. This suggests that the reachability     │
│ analysis within `ipsccp` has incorrectly determined that a block is dead when it is, in │
│ fact, still reachable.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe `opt` log provides a      │
│ crucial clue right before the crash:\n\n```\n  BasicBlock Dead:\nloop:                  │
│ ; preds = %loop, %entry\n  %add = or i32 0, 0\n  %cond = icmp eq i32 %arg, 1\n  br i1   │
│ %cond, label %exit, label %loop\n```\n\nThis shows that `ipsccp` has marked the `loop`  │
│ block as dead. However, the log also correctly states that this block has predecessors: │
│ `%loop` (a self-loop) and `%entry`. The `entry` block of a function is the designated   │
│ entry point, and in all the `callee` functions in your reproducer, `entry` has an       │
│ unconditional branch to `loop`. Therefore, if the function itself is considered live,   │
│ the `loop` block must also be live.\n\nThe assertion fails because `ipsccp` tries to    │
│ delete `loop` without first removing the edge from its predecessor, `entry`.\n\n### 3.  │
│ Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe core of the problem lies in how `ipsccp` handles function    │
│ specialization and subsequent reachability analysis.\n\n1.  **Function                  │
│ Specialization**: `ipsccp` specializes the `callee` functions based on their constant   │
│ arguments. For instance, it creates `callee.specialized.1` for the call `callee(i32     │
│ 1)`.\n2.  **Block Liveness Tracking**: The pass uses a `LiveBlocks` set to track all    │
│ reachable basic blocks.\n3.  **The Bug**: When a function is cloned for specialization, │
│ `ipsccp` correctly populates the `LiveBlocks` set for the *new, specialized* function.  │
│ However, it **fails to clear the `LiveBlocks` set from the previous function it         │
│ analyzed**.\n\nThis leads to a state where `LiveBlocks` contains a mix of blocks from   │
│ multiple functions. When `ipsccp` proceeds to the transformation phase, it iterates     │
│ through the basic blocks of the *original, unspecialized* `callee` function. It checks  │
│ if each block is in the (now-corrupted) `LiveBlocks` set.\n\nIn your case, the `entry`  │
│ block of the original `callee` is not found in `LiveBlocks` because the set was last    │
│ populated with blocks from a specialized clone. Mistakenly believing `entry` is dead,   │
│ `ipsccp` also considers its successor, `loop`, to be dead. It then attempts to delete   │
│ `loop`, but since the CFG of the original `callee` is still intact, `loop` still has    │
│ `entry` as a predecessor, triggering the `DomTreeUpdater` assertion.\n\nThe fix is      │
│ straightforward: we must clear the `LiveBlocks` set before beginning the analysis of    │
│ each new function within the main `runIPSCCP` loop.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit             │
│ Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to add `LiveBlocks.clear()` at the beginning of the function     │
│ processing loop in `runIPSCCP`.\n\n**File**:                                            │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/SCCP.cpp`\n\n```cpp\n233         // Run SCCP on the            │
│ function.\n234         LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << \"SCCP: Visiting: \" << F.getName() <<      │
│ '\\n');\n235         Changed = true;\n236                                               │
│ DTU.applyUpdates({{DominatorTree::Delete, F.getEntryBlock().getTerminator(),\n237       │
│ nullptr}});\n238         Solver.solve();\n239 \n240         // At this point, the       │
│ lattice values for all of the instructions in the\n241         // function are stable.  │
│ If the function is now known to be dead, remove it.\n242         if                     │
│ (Solver.isBlockExecutable(&F.getEntryBlock())) {\n243           // The function is      │
│ live, so iterate through all the blocks in the function,\n244           // replacing    │
│ instructions with constants if we have found them.\n245           for (BasicBlock &BB : │
│ F)\n246             if (Solver.isBlockExecutable(&BB)) {\n247                           │
│ LiveBlocks.insert(&BB);\n248             } else {\n249               // This block is   │
│ dead, so remove it.\n250               NumRemoved++;\n251                               │
│ DTU.deleteBB(&BB);\n252             }\n253         } else {\n```\n\n**Proposed          │
│ Edit**:\n\n```cpp\n233         // Run SCCP on the function.\n234                        │
│ LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << \"SCCP: Visiting: \" << F.getName() << '\\n');\n235                │
│ Changed = true;\n236         DTU.applyUpdates({{DominatorTree::Delete,                  │
│ F.getEntryBlock().getTerminator(),\n237                             nullptr}});\n238    │
│ LiveBlocks.clear();\n239         Solver.solve();\n240 \n241         // At this point,   │
│ the lattice values for all of the instructions in the\n242         // function are      │
│ stable. If the function is now known to be dead, remove it.\n243         if             │
│ (Solver.isBlockExecutable(&F.getEntryBlock())) {\n244           // The function is      │
│ live, so iterate through all the blocks in the function,\n245           // replacing    │
│ instructions with constants if we have found them.\n246           for (BasicBlock &BB : │
│ F)\n247             if (Solver.isBlockExecutable(&BB)) {\n248                           │
│ LiveBlocks.insert(&BB);\n249             } else {\n250               // This block is   │
│ dead, so remove it.\n251               NumRemoved++;\n252                               │
│ DTU.deleteBB(&BB);\n253             }\n254         } else {\n```\n\n### 5.              │
│ Conclusion\n\nThe bug is caused by stale reachability information (`LiveBlocks`) being  │
│ carried over between the analyses of different functions (specifically, between an      │
│ original function and its specialized clone). By clearing `LiveBlocks` before analyzing │
│ each function, we ensure that the reachability analysis is correct for the function     │
│ currently being processed, preventing the illegal attempt to delete a reachable basic   │
│ block."})                                                                               │
